Production at J.M. Smucker's (NYSE: SJM) new manufacturing facility and distribution center in McCalla, Alabama was expected to begin in **calendar year 2025**.

Details and reasoning:
- In November 2021, J.M. Smucker announced a $1.1 billion investment to build a new manufacturing facility and distribution center in McCalla, Alabama, dedicated to production of Smucker's Uncrustables sandwiches. The company's press release stated: "Construction of the facility is expected to begin no later than January 2022, with production commencing in calendar year 2025."
- This timeline was reaffirmed in the company's fiscal 2024 Form 10-K (fiscal year ended April 30, 2024): "Construction of this facility began in 2022, with production expected to begin in 2025," and in the Properties section: "Production is expected to begin at the McCalla facility during 2025." The 10-K also noted that despite an equipment fire in Q4 fiscal 2024, the company did "not anticipate a significant delay in beginning production in 2025."
- Note: Per the company's more recent quarterly filings (10-Qs for the quarters ended October 31, 2024 and January 31, 2025), production at the McCalla facility actually did begin on schedule — "production began during the second quarter of fiscal 2025" (i.e., the fiscal quarter ended October 31, 2024, which falls within calendar year 2024/2025 fiscal timing). The overall project (construction and production) is being executed in three phases over multiple years.

So, as originally announced and as disclosed in SEC filings, production at the McCalla, Alabama facility (which includes the distribution center) was expected to begin in 2025, and it has since commenced (during the company's second quarter of fiscal 2025).

